tclyffe in Clyst Hydon, Ratcliffes in Thorverton, and Ratcliffes in Broad Clyst (all Devon), Ratcliff in Stepney (Middlesex), and Rackley in Compton Bishop (Somerset). The placenames derive from Old English <i>rēad</i> ‘red’ + <i>clif</i> ‘cliff, bank, steep slope’ (see also   Rutley  ). A family of the name <i>Radcliffe</i> trace their descent from Sir Nicholas <i>de Radclyffe</i>. He is said to have been a knight who held the major of Radcliffe in Lancashire and served Roger de Poitou, Baron de Marsey in the 11th century."]}]},{"name":"Iola","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant of   Iole  , now the more frequent spelling."],"variants":[{"name":"Iole","meanings":["Pronounced ‘eye-<b>oh</b>-lee’: name borne in classical mythology by a daughter of  Eurytus of Oechalia . Herakles' infatuation with her led to his murder by his wife Deianeira. It represents the classical Greek vocabulary word meaning ‘violet’, and may in part have been chosen as a learned response to the 19th-century vogue for given names derived from words denoting flowers and plants."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Iola de Radcliffe was born in 1208, in England, United Kingdom, her father, Richard de Radcliffe, was 27 and her mother, Ellen Balderston, was 24. She married John De Rigmaiden II in 1224, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died in her hometown."},"et":{"1208–":"1208–Surnud","1208–Female":"1208–Surnud","1206–1305":"1206–1305","1280–1319":"1280–1319","1182–Male":"1182–Surnud","1185–Female":"1185–Surnud","1305":"1305","1206":"1206","1224":"1224","Abt 1200":"umbes 1200","1185":"1185","1182":"1182","1319":"1319","1208":"1208","1280":"1280","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Preston, Lancashire, England":"Preston, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1208–":"1208–Kuollut","1208–Female":"1208–Kuollut","1206–1305":"1206–1305","1280–1319":"1280–1319","1182–